  "prompt": "What is the difference between O- and O+?",
  "response": "The terms **O- (O negative)** and **O+ (O positive)** refer to **blood types** based on the **ABO blood group system** and the presence or absence of the **Rh factor**. Here's a breakdown of the differences:\n\n### 1. **ABO Blood Group**\n   - Both **O-** and **O+** belong to the **O blood group**, which means they **lack A and B antigens** on the surface of red blood cells.\n\n### 2. **Rh Factor**\n   - The **Rh factor** is a protein that can be present (Rh positive) or absent (Rh negative) on the surface of red blood cells.\n   - **O+ (O positive)**: Rh factor is **present**.\n   - **O- (O negative)**: Rh factor is **absent**.\n\n### 3. **Compatibility**\n   - **O-** is the **universal donor for red blood cells**. It can be given to patients of any blood type (A, B, AB, O) because it lacks A, B, and Rh antigens.\n   - **O+** can donate to **O+ and AB+** patients. It cannot be given to Rh-negative patients because it has the Rh factor.\n\n### 4. **Receiving Blood**\n   - **O-** can receive blood only from **O-** donors because it lacks the Rh factor.\n   - **O+** can receive blood from **O- and O+** donors.\n\n### 5. **Prevalence**\n   - **O+** is the **most common blood type** in many populations.\n   - **O-** is **less common** but highly valuable in emergencies due to its universal donor status.\n\n### Summary:\n- **O+**: Rh positive, can donate to O+ and AB+, can receive from O- and O+.\n- **O-**: Rh negative, universal donor for red blood cells, can receive only from O-.",
